Diabetes mellitus has become increasingly prevalent in recent years, the most 
dramatic increase being observed in younger women. Diabetes is a multiplier of 
cardiovascular risk and decreases life expectancy more in women than in men. 
Diabetic women are less likely to achieve therapeutic targets for cardiovascular 
risk factors and to be optimally treated. They present more often with atypical 
symptoms that cause delays in timely recognition and management of 
